  "descriptionKey": [
    "This indicator tracks how much a government spends on education at a specific level annually, adjusted for inflation and differences in the cost of living. Spending is expressed in constant [international-$](#dod:int_dollar_abbreviation), which allows for comparisons across countries and over time.",
    "It includes all forms of public education spending — from teacher salaries and textbooks to school maintenance, capital projects like building classrooms, and external funding from international donors that flows through government budgets.",
    "Figures are initially reported in local currency, then converted using purchasing power parity (PPP) exchange rates and adjusted to a constant base year. This ensures the numbers reflect real resource commitments rather than changes in local prices or currency fluctuations.",
    "This measure provides a comparable view of how much governments invest in education in absolute terms. But it doesn’t show how spending is distributed or how effectively it’s used — it should be interpreted alongside indicators like enrolment and per-student spending."
  ],
